definitions.definition: To disagree with or oppose something or someone; ( especially in a Court of Law ) to raise an objection .
examples: I object to the proposal to build a new airport terminal.
We strongly object to sending her to jail for ten years.

definitions.definition: To offer in opposition as a criminal charge or by way of accusation or reproach; to adduce as an objection or adverse reason.
To set before or against; to bring into opposition; to oppose.

main_definition: ( intransitive ) To disagree with or oppose something or someone; ( especially in a Court of Law ) to raise an objection .
secondary_definitions: ( transitive , obsolete ) To offer in opposition as a criminal charge or by way of accusation or reproach; to adduce as an objection or adverse reason.
( transitive , obsolete ) To set before or against; to bring into opposition; to oppose.
